>    Hi Dora, JB, and Yarik,

>    I think, as I understand the call, that this is primarily a software
>    ecosystem maintenance and sustainability opportunity rather than a
>    research award. My interpretation is that the focus is less on
>    developing entirely new tools and more on maturing the usability,
>    interoperability, sustainability, governance, and long-term support of
>    foundational community infrastructure.

>    That is why I previously asked whether this was intended as a research
>    proposal. What was pitched sounded more like a research-oriented
>    effort, namely the development of something novel in the way an
>    individual laboratory might pursue, but it was less clear to me how the
>    proposed activities would directly strengthen or expand the BIDS
>    ecosystem itself.

>    For this particular call, my impression is that the proposal should
>    focus on activities such as:

>    (A) Expanding the coverage of data types and derivatives supported
>    within BIDS
>    (B) Developing mechanisms to engage more tool developers and improve
>    compatibility across the ecosystem
>    (C) Increasing community adoption, usability, training, documentation,
>    and sustainability
>    (D) Major refactoring of BIDS like BIDS 2.0

>    Other ecosystem-oriented activities also seem compatible with the RFA.
>    I may be missing something, however, as I am currently in transit and
>    may not have interpreted every aspect correctly.

>    On a separate topic regarding fiscal responsibility and organizational
>    support, the UT System recently established a new Office of Open
>    Science. My understanding is that one of their goals is precisely to
>    support and coordinate open-science infrastructure and sustainability
>    efforts across the system. I wonder whether they could potentially help
>    handle some of the fiscal and administrative aspects related to BIDS.
>    Since the office is newly established, they may also be motivated to
>    demonstrate capacity in this area. I would be happy to reach out and
>    explore this possibility if the group thinks it could be useful. I had
>    not raised it earlier because I thought the INCF arrangement was likely
>    to work out, and this office was only recently created.

>    To be clear, I am not saying that JB’s proposal is not interesting or
>    valuable. My only point is that, at least to me, it currently reads
>    more like a research proposal than a sustainability and ecosystem
>    proposal. A proposal like that could be more competitive in a standard
>    call and part of the funds could still be sent to BIDS maintainers.

>    Just my two cents.

>    Best,
>    Franco

